A Priority Queue (PQ) is an abstract data structure where:

every element has a priority
removal happens based on priority, not insertion order

So unlike a normal queue:

Structure	Removal Order
Queue	FIFO
Stack	LIFO
Priority Queue	Highest/Lowest priority first
Real Life Analogy

Imagine hospital emergency rooms.

Patients arrive in this order:

Mild fever
Accident victim
Headache
Heart attack

Doctor will NOT follow FIFO.

Instead:

Heart attack
Accident victim
Fever
Headache

So:

insertion order ≠ processing order
priority decides removal

That is exactly a Priority Queue.

Important Thing:
Priority Queue is NOT a specific data structure

It is a behavior / ADT (Abstract Data Type).

Just like:

Queue = concept
Stack = concept

Priority Queue only defines:

insert()
get/remove highest priority item

But HOW internally it is implemented can vary.

Possible implementations:

Array
Linked List
Balanced BST
Heap ← most common and efficient

That is why people say:

Heap is used to implement Priority Queue

NOT:

Heap == Priority Queue

Heap is just the engine behind it.

Core Operations of Priority Queue
Operation	Meaning
insert(x)	Add element
peek()	View highest priority element
poll()/remove()	Remove highest priority
isEmpty()	Check empty
Now Your Biggest Doubt:
"Who sets the priority?"

YOU do.

Priority is determined using:

natural ordering
OR
custom comparator
1. Natural Ordering (Default)

When using numbers:

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

Java automatically uses:

ascending order
smallest element gets highest priority

Example:

pq.add(30);
pq.add(10);
pq.add(20);

System.out.println(pq.poll());

Output:

10

Because:

smaller number = higher priority

This is called:

Min Priority Queue
Why ascending by default?

Because Java internally uses:

Comparable

For Integer:

10.compareTo(20)

returns negative → means 10 comes before 20.

So natural ascending ordering becomes priority.

Max Priority Queue

If you want:

bigger number = higher priority

You give comparator:

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq =
    new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());

Now:

30
20
10

gets removed in that order.

VERY IMPORTANT UNDERSTANDING

Priority does NOT mean:

only ascending
only descending

Priority can be ANY rule.

Examples:

Example 1: Student Marks

Higher marks = higher priority

class Student {
    int marks;
}

Comparator:

(a, b) -> b.marks - a.marks
Example 2: Task Scheduler

Earlier deadline = higher priority

(a, b) -> a.deadline - b.deadline
Example 3: Shortest Job First (OS)

Smaller execution time = higher priority

(a, b) -> a.time - b.time
Example 4: Uber Driver Matching

Closest driver = higher priority

(a, b) -> a.distance - b.distance
So Priority Queue is Basically:

"Remove elements according to some ranking rule."

That ranking rule is decided by:

Comparable
OR
Comparator
Java PriorityQueue Internals

Java class:

PriorityQueue<E>

belongs to:

java.util

Internally implemented using:

Binary Heap

You’ll study that next.

Key Characteristic That Confuses Beginners

Suppose:

PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

pq.add(30);
pq.add(10);
pq.add(20);

System.out.println(pq);

Output may look weird:

[10, 30, 20]

or

[10, 20, 30]

People think:

"Oh it keeps everything sorted"

NO.

VERY IMPORTANT:

Priority Queue is NOT fully sorted

It only guarantees:

Top element = highest priority

Remaining elements may not be fully ordered.

This is because heap only partially maintains order.

Then Why poll() Always Gives Correct Answer?

Because heap guarantees:

root contains highest priority element

Not full sorting.

You’ll deeply understand this once you study heaps.

Time Complexities

(when implemented using heap)

Operation	Complexity
insert	O(log n)
poll/remove	O(log n)
peek	O(1)
Why Not Use Sorting Instead?

Suppose every insertion sorts array:

Insert = O(n log n)

Too expensive.

Heap gives:

O(log n)

much better.

