Java Example — Min Heap PQ
PriorityQueue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();

pq.add(40);
pq.add(10);
pq.add(30);
pq.add(20);

while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
    System.out.println(pq.poll());
}

Output:

10
20
30
40
Java Example — Max Heap PQ
PriorityQueue<Integer> pq =
    new PriorityQueue<>(Collections.reverseOrder());

pq.add(40);
pq.add(10);
pq.add(30);
pq.add(20);

while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
    System.out.println(pq.poll());
}

Output:

40
30
20
10
Custom Comparator Example
class Student {
    String name;
    int marks;

    Student(String name, int marks) {
        this.name = name;
        this.marks = marks;
    }
}

PriorityQueue<Student> pq =
    new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> b.marks - a.marks);

pq.add(new Student("A", 70));
pq.add(new Student("B", 90));
pq.add(new Student("C", 80));

System.out.println(pq.poll().name);

Output:

B

Because highest marks got highest priority.

One More Important Thing
Priority Queue vs Heap

This confusion is VERY common.

Priority Queue	Heap
Abstract behavior	Concrete data structure
Defines operations	Implements operations
"What it should do"	"How it does it"
Can be implemented many ways	One efficient implementation

Same as:

Concept	Implementation
List	ArrayList
Queue	LinkedList
Priority Queue	Heap
